you had 50 sheep you could make this pattern
say, "Well this is how much I've got." So

00:17:02.420 --> 00:17:08.699
it was much easier for keeping track of your
stock and also for doing trade. And that really

00:17:08.699 --> 00:17:12.900
--. And those were the first things that you
can call numbers which is a system of words

00:17:12.900 --> 00:17:15.209
and symbols for numbers.

00:17:15.209 --> 00:17:19.089
And what's interesting, as well as being the
first time that words and symbols were used

00:17:19.089 --> 00:17:24.980
for numbers, it's the first of any scripts,
so all literature or any of the Western writing

00:17:24.980 --> 00:17:32.730
systems emerged from these first kind of Sumerian
accountants really developing this system.

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:36.130
Now before they had the system, humans would
be able to tell the difference between one

00:17:36.130 --> 00:17:40.340
thing and two things it's just that we didn't
have the words, the abstract nouns and the

00:17:40.340 --> 00:17:43.070
symbols for one and two.

00:17:43.070 --> 00:17:47.270
So what is it that numbers bring us 'cause
most people think, "Well numbers they're so

00:17:47.270 --> 00:17:53.160
natural they must have been here sort of forever."
Well now you know 6,000, 7,000 years in the

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:58.080
history of civilization is really not very
much and they are new and it's because they

00:17:58.080 --> 00:18:00.160
combine two different things.

00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:01.160
[pause]

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:07.330
Anyone who's studied sort of the philosophy
of maths or maths will know all this, but

00:18:07.330 --> 00:18:10.010
most people I think are quite surprised they
think that you can't make anything simpler

00:18:10.010 --> 00:18:11.460
than a number, it's obvious what it is. First
of all, you can divide it, it has two separate

00:18:11.460 --> 00:18:13.059
parts, it has cardinality and ordinality,
those are just the sort of long words for

00:18:13.059 --> 00:18:14.059
amount and position.

00:18:14.059 --> 00:18:23.240
So the cardinality of the number of chairs
in the front row is gonna be five 'cause there

00:18:23.240 --> 00:18:29.240
are five of them there. But when I say, "Count
to ten," one, two, three, four, five, six,

00:18:29.240 --> 00:18:33.990
seven, eight, nine, ten I'm not counting things.
So five is literally just what comes in the

00:18:33.990 --> 00:18:37.650
position after four and before six.

00:18:37.650 --> 00:18:42.820
So I was thinking, "Well how can I bring this
out to sort of explain that it's not obvious,

00:18:42.820 --> 00:18:48.049
these are two very different things?" And
then I realized that there are some non-humans

00:18:48.049 --> 00:18:53.300
who have been taught to count and they are
chimpanzees and they're in Japan. And so I

00:18:53.300 --> 00:18:57.450
called up the travel agent and flew there,
flew to Japan to meet these chimpanzees.

00:18:57.450 --> 00:19:08.670
How do you teach a chimpanzee to count? Well
you have to teach the cardinality of a number

00:19:08.670 --> 00:19:09.670
and the ordinality of a number.

00:19:09.670 --> 00:19:10.670
[pause]

00:19:10.670 --> 00:19:15.679
In the early 80s when Japan was sort of pioneering
in touch screen computers they got a chimpanzee

00:19:15.679 --> 00:19:21.180
called Ai from West Africa and started to
teach her both the cardinality and the ordinality

00:19:21.180 --> 00:19:25.700
using these touch screen computers. And so
it was reward driven: you set a task and if

00:19:25.700 --> 00:19:32.390
they get it right they get a bit of food like
shoots down the sides. If they get it wrong

00:19:32.390 --> 00:19:35.470
they don't get the food. So they end up only
wanting to do what gets them food so that's

00:19:35.470 --> 00:19:36.470
how they work it out.

00:19:36.470 --> 00:19:39.780
And so cardinality what would happen they
would show and sort of say different boxes

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:44.340
with say different numbers of carrots or colored
pencils in them and they would have to then

00:19:44.340 --> 00:19:49.700
tap the symbol for the digit of how many were
currently referring to that. And also visa

00:19:49.700 --> 00:19:54.370
versa, they'd be given a digit say four and
they they'd have a selection of boxes with

00:19:54.370 --> 00:19:59.360
different objects in, they'd have to tap the
box which corresponded to number four. Didn't

00:19:59.360 --> 00:20:02.870
take very long for Ai to learn how to do that.

00:20:02.870 --> 00:20:07.230
Ordinality, what they would do they would
show two digits, say six and seven, so single

00:20:07.230 --> 00:20:12.549
digits between one and nine, and the chimpanzee
had to learn to press the lowest one and then

00:20:12.549 --> 00:20:17.600
the highest one in order to get the food.
They learned that pretty quick as well.

00:20:17.600 --> 00:20:24.179
So in the late '80s you could say that there
was a chimpanzee who had learned the Arabic

00:20:24.179 --> 00:20:33.300
numeral system because had a working, functional
knowledge of both cardinality and ordinality.

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:36.590
Then the chief researcher there realized,

00:20:36.590 --> 00:20:37.590
[pause]

00:20:37.590 --> 00:20:44.450
"We've not taught the chimpanzee zero. Why
don't we teach the chimpanzee the cardinality

00:20:44.450 --> 00:20:52.330
of zero and then see if the chimpanzee can
work out what the ordinality is?" So for us

00:20:52.330 --> 00:20:56.299
it's just like dead easy, yeah it's below
one, it's less than one, so yeah it's gonna

00:20:56.299 --> 00:21:04.140
be zero's before one, one is more than zero.
We get that; it's so obvious to us. So is

00:21:04.140 --> 00:21:07.380
it obvious to a chimpanzee? So what they did
first they taught the chimpanzee the cardinality

00:21:07.380 --> 00:21:09.950
of zero, when there's a zero there there's
a box with nothing in. When there's a box

00:21:09.950 --> 00:21:12.470
with nothing in it's a zero.

00:21:12.470 --> 00:21:17.910
And then they did the ordinality test: they
showed two digits of which sometimes one was

00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:24.630
a zero and they waited to see which number
the chimpanzee would touch first. Often I

00:21:24.630 --> 00:21:29.001
have to hesitate when I say chimpanzee 'cause
I want to say monkey, but a chimpanzee is

00:21:29.001 --> 00:21:32.630
not monkeys they're apes and apes and monkey
are very different. And once when I was there

00:21:32.630 --> 00:21:36.910
interviewing these people about it I accidentally
referred to one of their chimpanzees as a

00:21:36.910 --> 00:21:39.250
monkey and my God [laughs]

00:21:39.250 --> 00:21:40.250
[laughter]

00:21:40.250 --> 00:21:44.200
it was ugly. [laughs] 'Cause when you work
with chimpanzees, because they're so like

00:21:44.200 --> 00:21:51.080
close to us, they're called students and the
lab is called a classroom, it's like kinda

00:21:51.080 --> 00:21:52.080
weird, but it's kinda brilliant too.

00:21:52.080 --> 00:21:56.630
So they taught the chimpanzee the cardinality
of zero, came to the ordinality,

00:21:56.630 --> 00:21:57.630
[pause]

00:21:57.630 --> 00:22:01.910
did it a bunch of times and then did the average
amount of times of when the chimpanzee, which

00:22:01.910 --> 00:22:06.059
numbers they were and when it was the zero
tapped first, when it was tapped second. And

00:22:06.059 --> 00:22:07.059
where was zero?

00:22:07.059 --> 00:22:08.059
[pause]

00:22:08.059 --> 00:22:12.660
It was between six and seven. So even though
they understood the cardinality of zero they

00:22:12.660 --> 00:22:19.470
had no idea about where it was, on the number
line it's less than one. So they did this

00:22:19.470 --> 00:22:21.799
test more and more and more and obviously
because they're getting food when they get

00:22:21.799 --> 00:22:27.990
it right they're kind of learning and so gradually
the position of zero over the number line

00:22:27.990 --> 00:22:33.540
got less and less and less and less but it
never really got below one. It was always,

00:22:33.540 --> 00:22:37.480
they were always confused about where the
zero and one were sort of more or less the

00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:38.800
same thing.

00:22:38.800 --> 00:22:45.679
That I think really shows that what makes
it distinctive for us humans is that we can

00:22:45.679 --> 00:22:50.730
slip between cardinality and ordinality very
easily and chimpanzees cannot.

00:22:50.730 --> 00:22:53.030
But while they cannot do that --

00:22:53.030 --> 00:22:55.400
[pause]

00:22:55.400 --> 00:23:01.210
the Primate Research Institute in Kyoto, in
Inuyama but synced to the Kyoto University

00:23:01.210 --> 00:23:06.270
had, now they've got about 15 chimpanzees
that can manipulate numbers amazingly well.

00:23:06.270 --> 00:23:10.650
And they thought, "Well let's try and use
these skills to see if we can find out anything

00:23:10.650 --> 00:23:16.480
else about the cognitive capacities of chimpanzees."
And what they found was that in some cases,

00:23:16.480 --> 00:23:21.270
they'd never thought this before, chimpanzees
have a higher cognitive ability than humans

