00:26:28.850 --> 00:26:34.020
Now I went all around the world and went out
to Japan to see the chimpanzees. I was probably

00:26:34.020 --> 00:26:39.660
the first guy to go on like a maths tour of
Japan. I wanted to see anything to do with

00:26:39.660 --> 00:26:45.880
numbers and digits. And I learned that even
though we think that maths is the same all

00:26:45.880 --> 00:26:50.169
over the world because one and one is two
everywhere, our approach to maths and the

00:26:50.169 --> 00:26:53.880
cultural resonance is very, very different.
And sometimes even the simplest way and I

00:26:53.880 --> 00:26:58.039
think it's good to think about this because
it makes us kind of just challenges some of

00:26:58.039 --> 00:27:01.850
our own preconceptions about what maths is,
what numbers are, where they come from.

00:27:01.850 --> 00:27:09.299
The most obvious one is tallying. I grew up
in the U.K. and you tally like this: one,

00:27:09.299 --> 00:27:14.070
two, three, four, five. Obvious, surely the
simplest way, surely they've been doing this

00:27:14.070 --> 00:27:21.780
since we were sort of cavemen tallying in
caves and no one does it any other way, but

00:27:21.780 --> 00:27:22.780
that's wrong. I don't know if there any South
Americans,

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:24.720
[pause]

00:27:24.720 --> 00:27:31.360
in the audience, non-Venezuelan South Americans
'cause Venezuelans do it like this because

00:27:31.360 --> 00:27:33.950
the Venezuelans kind of do everything like
America. If you're not a Venezuelan South

00:27:33.950 --> 00:27:42.020
American this is how you tally: one, two,
three, four, five which actually is a much,

00:27:42.020 --> 00:27:46.780
much better way than the way we do it because
here three and four is always different, you're

00:27:46.780 --> 00:27:49.790
never gonna confuse it, whereas as I said
before three and four you would confuse it

00:27:49.790 --> 00:27:54.720
'cause at four you have to start counting
the lines. So if you see a bunch of guys in

00:27:54.720 --> 00:27:59.270
Brazil playing Dominoes, that's how they're
counting their scores.

00:27:59.270 --> 00:28:02.090
In the Far East though in Japan, I see if
there's any Japanese, Chinese, or Korean people

00:28:02.090 --> 00:28:07.260
in the audience if you are, be quiet. 'Cause
this is how you tally in these countries:

00:28:07.260 --> 00:28:08.260
[pause]

00:28:08.260 --> 00:28:14.260
one, any guess where the next one's gonna
come from? From there two, three, four, five.

00:28:14.260 --> 00:28:21.590
Is that that really confusing and complicated
and like designed to like turn people off

00:28:21.590 --> 00:28:26.140
counting? Actually it's beautiful 'cause what
