00:28:44.730 --> 00:28:47.679
I mean I didn't believe it and I asked myself
a nice little party trick. Whenever you go

00:28:47.679 --> 00:28:49.909
to, that's how they tally.

00:28:49.909 --> 00:28:50.909
Now --

00:28:50.909 --> 00:28:51.909
[pause]

00:28:51.909 --> 00:28:57.910
I saw lots of different people in Japan and
one of the most fun people I met with this

00:28:57.910 --> 00:29:00.440
guy here, Maki Kaji, and he's the guy who,
I wouldn't say invented he sort of reinvented

00:29:00.440 --> 00:29:01.610
Sudoku but probably the most important guy
in the history of Sudoku.

00:29:01.610 --> 00:29:05.330
Sudoku was actually invented in the late '70s
by an amateur puzzle maker in America, when

00:29:05.330 --> 00:29:16.780
it was a small American puzzle magazine but
in a few Times and no one took any notice.

00:29:16.780 --> 00:29:22.289
And then Maki Kaji in the early '80s was trying
to start a Japanese puzzle magazine, saw this

00:29:22.289 --> 00:29:26.580
American puzzle magazine, most of it was word
puzzles could understand anything about it,

00:29:26.580 --> 00:29:29.110
about those ones. Saw the number puzzle one,
thought it was brilliant.

00:29:29.110 --> 00:29:33.770
So he adapted it and now the givens in a Sudoku
are all parallel a bit like in a crosswords

00:29:33.770 --> 00:29:37.090
and he coined the phrase, I think he registered
it, Sudoku, which means "the number appears

00:29:37.090 --> 00:29:42.309
only once" and then it became a bit of a hit
in Japan and then since it came to Europe

00:29:42.309 --> 00:29:46.860
about five years ago and around the rest of
the world. He's become quite wealthy and he

00:29:46.860 --> 00:29:50.325
says, "I'm not a mathematician. I'm more of
a numbers impresario; a kind of showman."

00:29:50.325 --> 00:29:55.090
And he loves gambling and he was saying, he's
in his 50's he looks a little younger, he

00:29:55.090 --> 00:30:01.730
said, "Thank God I didn't make all my money
when I was in my 30's and 40's; I would have

00:30:01.730 --> 00:30:07.680
spent it all on Geisha girls," and he's like
the least sort of nerdy numbers guy Japanese

00:30:07.680 --> 00:30:09.600
that you'd ever expect to meet.

00:30:09.600 --> 00:30:14.679
And what I loved about him is where ever he
saw, when he saw numbers he just was making

00:30:14.679 --> 00:30:20.530
games and having fun with them. And this is
what he told me his latest hobby was, taking

00:30:20.530 --> 00:30:25.890
pictures of Japanese car number plates. I
don't know if anyone here can maybe see why

00:30:25.890 --> 00:30:32.280
he might want to, sort of a good Google question
for [chuckles] These number plates are mathematically

00:30:32.280 --> 00:30:33.280
interesting --

00:30:33.280 --> 00:30:34.280
[pause]

00:30:34.280 --> 00:30:39.110
it's because they're aligned to the times
table, three times five is fifteen and four

00:30:39.110 --> 00:30:43.160
times one is four. So actually there are eighty-one
different types of registration license plate

00:30:43.160 --> 00:30:49.121
in Japan and he was going around where ever
he saw one the motorway or the car park he

00:30:49.121 --> 00:30:53.050
would just take its picture and his idea was
to have an exhibition of the times tables

00:30:53.050 --> 00:30:55.400
as seen on car license plates.

00:30:55.400 --> 00:30:56.400
[laughter]

00:30:56.400 --> 00:31:01.080
I thought that was just sort of brilliant
and you don't need to be a math genius to

00:31:01.080 --> 00:31:05.970
appreciate the sort of the beauty and the
simplicity in that.

00:31:05.970 --> 00:31:07.580
[pause]

00:31:07.580 --> 00:31:13.140
In Japan, probably the greatest way that their
approach to maths and numbers is different

00:31:13.140 --> 00:31:22.940
to in the U.K. and in America, certainly,
is in the presence of the abacus. Now this

00:31:22.940 --> 00:31:27.140
is an abacus. An abacus is a counting machine
or a calculating machine. It's really the

00:31:27.140 --> 00:31:33.900
oldest kind of calculating machine that there
is and virtually all cultures that count have

00:31:33.900 --> 00:31:39.480
similar things. Sometimes they don't make
them into mechanical objects they're just

00:31:39.480 --> 00:31:51.429
lines and you have sort of say pebbles on
a counter. That's where the word counter comes

00:31:51.429 --> 00:31:56.059
from where you'd have little counting things.
And the abacus --

00:31:56.059 --> 00:31:57.059
[pause]

00:31:57.059 --> 00:31:58.300
a Japanese abacus called the soroban has five
beads per rod so there are ten positions per

00:31:58.300 --> 00:32:00.880
rod so they represent the numbers from zero
to nine. It should be horizontal so there's

00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:05.030
no, gravity isn't working. And at the top
the bead can either be at the top or the bottom,

00:32:05.030 --> 00:32:10.429
black is the bottom. So you start with naught.
These four here would be naught, one, the

00:32:10.429 --> 00:32:14.120
bottom goes up; two, the two would go up;
three, three goes up; four, four goes up;

00:32:14.120 --> 00:32:20.460
and five they all go down and the top one
goes down to go five. So it's kind of like

00:32:20.460 --> 00:32:23.460
a little base five with the base ten there.

00:32:23.460 --> 00:32:29.470
Now you do not need, once you get good at
the abacus it's very easy to do additions,

00:32:29.470 --> 00:32:31.400
subtraction 'cause just by putting in the
sum you've done the addition already and multiplication

00:32:31.400 --> 00:32:38.360
is essentially a little bit more complicated
addition so you can do additions, square roots,

00:32:38.360 --> 00:32:45.549
division, all that really, really quickly
using an abacus. And in fact up until the

00:32:45.549 --> 00:32:57.450
pocket calculator in Japan and from Russia,
eastwards, actually, everyone would learn

00:32:57.450 --> 00:32:59.030
to calculate using an abacus.

00:32:59.030 --> 00:33:03.900
And actually I've brought this item on here
which came out ?

00:33:03.900 --> 00:33:04.900
[pause]

00:33:04.900 --> 00:33:10.260
in Japan in the '70s when the pocket calculator
was becoming popular. And you might think

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:16.290
that this abacus calculator is to, you do
the sum on the abacus and then you just check

00:33:16.290 --> 00:33:18.720
whether you're right with a calculator. But
obviously it was completely the other way

00:33:18.720 --> 00:33:23.159
around 'cause they didn't trust this so they
would do it here and they would just check

00:33:23.159 --> 00:33:25.900
on the abacus just to see if they got it right.
[laughs]

00:33:25.900 --> 00:33:26.900
[laughter]

00:33:26.900 --> 00:33:31.600
Now the phrase for reading, writing, arithmetic
in Japanese is yonde, kaki, soroban; reading,

00:33:31.600 --> 00:33:37.679
writing, soroban. So it's very kind of culturey;
it's something in their culture. And even

00:33:37.679 --> 00:33:42.220
though you do not need to use an abacus in
daily life at all, you don't even need to

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:48.539
use it for the school maths syllabus, still
a million Japanese kids every year study the

00:33:48.539 --> 00:33:54.150
