of after they're called jukus where it's sort

00:33:54.150 --> 00:33:55.730
of after school clubs.

00:33:55.730 --> 00:34:01.409
And Japan has this kind of tradition of these
jukus for other things, after school clubs.

00:34:01.409 --> 00:34:07.340
Monday you might wanna do violin practice,
Tuesday baseball, Wednesday soroban. And I

00:34:07.340 --> 00:34:08.879
went to one to see what they did.

00:34:08.879 --> 00:34:09.879
[pause]

00:34:09.879 --> 00:34:15.270
And this is basically what goes on in a soroban
school. You learn to calculate using the abacus.

00:34:15.270 --> 00:34:18.159
It's very competitive and you can get speeds
and when you get sort of good at it and because

00:34:18.159 --> 00:34:26.990
it's competitive the awards that you get are
just like a martial art. So if you get good

00:34:26.990 --> 00:34:32.790
you get your Dans and it goes up in Dans,
so just like in karate or whatever, I don't

00:34:32.790 --> 00:34:37.839
know anything about martial arts, but I know
that they use Dans, they use Dans in the abacus.

00:34:37.839 --> 00:34:42.109
And I went to a competition, 'cause they have
lots of competitions. This is a regional competition,

00:34:42.109 --> 00:34:48.010
there were maybe a couple of hundred kids
doing it and it was several hours on their

00:34:48.010 --> 00:34:53.030
Sunday. And this is them just, the person's
reading out sums and they're calculating as

00:34:53.030 --> 00:34:59.280
fast as possible. This is the sums being read
out and this is what you win, these wonderful

00:34:59.280 --> 00:35:05.030
winged figures holding sort of golden soroban,
that's fantastic.

00:35:05.030 --> 00:35:10.660
Now why do people learn the soroban? And why
would you want to calculate really fast mentally

00:35:10.660 --> 00:35:16.890
if you don't really need to? And I asked this
guy, Yugi Miyamoto, who this is his kind of

00:35:16.890 --> 00:35:23.520
group of soroban pupils, why and he just looked
and me and just didn't really understand the

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:28.801
question. And he said, "Well why would you
ever want to run for 26 miles? But people

00:35:28.801 --> 00:35:34.000
do." He said, "There's this idea that why
not practice something that the body, the

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:38.580
human can do, as best possible, and running
in sports what about the kind of the brain

00:35:38.580 --> 00:35:41.440
muscle as well to kind of practice that."

00:35:41.440 --> 00:35:46.560
And also I could see that the kids were really,
they were really having fun. There's something

00:35:46.560 --> 00:35:50.250
about learning with the abacus, there's something
kind of visceral about the counting that makes

00:35:50.250 --> 00:35:52.380
people enjoy it a lot more.

00:35:52.380 --> 00:35:57.300
Now I was kind of fascinated by the soroban
and then Yugi Miyamoto made me more fascinated

00:35:57.300 --> 00:36:03.690
by telling me about something called anzan.
Anzan is if you can do the abacus really well

00:36:03.690 --> 00:36:10.410
after while you don't need to have a physical
abacus anymore to do the same calculations

00:36:10.410 --> 00:36:15.962
'cause you can visualize the abacus in your
brain, right? So I said, "Well what do you

00:36:15.962 --> 00:36:19.450
mean?" He said, "Okay," and he got one of
his top pupils and then just said something

00:36:19.450 --> 00:36:23.320
it was like I don't know 57 times 221 and
the guy just gave the answer.

00:36:23.320 --> 00:36:26.680
And I said, "Well, what's going on in your
brain?" He said, "Yeah, I have like eight

00:36:26.680 --> 00:36:31.620
rows, eight columns with the beads in my brain
and I just like moving them around."

00:36:31.620 --> 00:36:32.620
[pause]

00:36:32.620 --> 00:36:36.859
It's absolutely amazing and Yugi Miyamoto
decided to sort of, 'cause there's something

00:36:36.859 --> 00:36:41.900
very Japanese about it, he wanted to kind
of publicize it more. So he thought, "Why

00:36:41.900 --> 00:36:46.270
don't I think up a game, some kind of counting
task which the only way of solving it is using

00:36:46.270 --> 00:36:50.690
anzan?" So if you were to say 25 times 26
say.

00:36:50.690 --> 00:36:51.690
[pause]

00:36:51.690 --> 00:36:55.650
Millions of ways you could solve it: you could
