00:42:07.980 --> 00:42:14.210
probably don't even know what a slide rule
is. A slide rule uses logarithms to, you can

00:42:14.210 --> 00:42:19.030
do multiplications and divisions, square roots
very easily by sliding two log scales against

00:42:19.030 --> 00:42:21.250
each other. And,

00:42:21.250 --> 00:42:22.250
[pause]

00:42:22.250 --> 00:42:29.109
when the logarithms were invented about 400
years ago.

00:42:29.109 --> 00:42:30.240
[pause]

00:42:30.240 --> 00:42:33.570
A couple decades later the slide rule was
invented and it totally revolutionized science.

00:42:33.570 --> 00:42:37.770
Straight away you could do long complicated
calculations very quickly and probably every

00:42:37.770 --> 00:42:44.540
single great invention of the last 350, 400
years required a slide rule. Right up until

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:49.890
you can almost date it it's like August 1974
when Sinclair's pocket calculator came out

00:42:49.890 --> 00:42:55.930
and no one needed them anymore. So nothing
has been so dominate and then died so quickly.

00:42:55.930 --> 00:43:01.790
And actually I can remember and also from
movies in the sort of '50s and '60s the slide

00:43:01.790 --> 00:43:06.610
rule was this sort of really quite boring
like two sticks like really sort of dull people

00:43:06.610 --> 00:43:09.630
would have them like in their top pocket.
But actually for hundreds of years there are

00:43:09.630 --> 00:43:14.760
sort of beautiful ones were made and every
industry, every trade had their own type of

00:43:14.760 --> 00:43:15.760
slide rule.

00:43:15.760 --> 00:43:20.630
And when I was sitting at this guy's house
these collections they were gorgeous. This

00:43:20.630 --> 00:43:26.900
one is from the 1890's which the log scales,
you pull them out, and that called Thacher's

00:43:26.900 --> 00:43:29.390
Calculating Instrument.

00:43:29.390 --> 00:43:35.329
This one here was the most amazing. Also in
the 1890's, it's called Professor Fuller's

00:43:35.329 --> 00:43:42.609
Calculator and the scales were on a helix
running to about 45 feet. So you could do

00:43:42.609 --> 00:43:47.930
a calculation with this two five decimals
places. So normally most slide rules they're

00:43:47.930 --> 00:43:51.320
only analog because you're looking on the
stick to see where something goes, you get

00:43:51.320 --> 00:43:56.820
about three decimal places. And five decimals
places for most types of engineering is more

00:43:56.820 --> 00:44:07.430
than enough. So it's amazing to think that
something could get you, could calculate within

00:44:07.430 --> 00:44:11.109
seconds complicated sums of five decimal places
120 years ago.

