00:44:46.720 --> 00:44:54.500
So Pascal, 400 odd years ago, had this dream
for mechanized calculating and he invented

00:44:54.500 --> 00:44:59.140
the Pascaline which is sort of the very first
one. And then Leibniz has its Step Reckoner,

00:44:59.140 --> 00:45:02.660
there's this whole history of people mechanizing
counting. That's where the word kind of number

00:45:02.660 --> 00:45:04.010
crunching comes from.

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:08.190
And there's the Victorian age and also the
early 20th century around until the mid-20th

00:45:08.190 --> 00:45:13.670
century people would have these big desks
sort of machines that would do all this calculating

00:45:13.670 --> 00:45:14.970
for them.

00:45:14.970 --> 00:45:18.990
Then in the 1930's Curt Herzstark, an Austrian,
had this idea for this new sort of system,

00:45:18.990 --> 00:45:25.630
an engineering system, that he can make a
pocket sized one. And it took him 20 years

00:45:25.630 --> 00:45:29.890
to work out exactly how to do it and he was
imprisoned for some of that time as a prisoner

00:45:29.890 --> 00:45:34.290
in Buchenwald Concentration Camp. And he was
half Jewish so he was going to be killed because

00:45:34.290 --> 00:45:39.310
the Germans knew he was working on this. They
didn't kill him and they said, "If you invent

00:45:39.310 --> 00:45:43.610
this we will present it to the Fuhrer and
you'll be declared Aryan and you will survive."

00:45:43.610 --> 00:45:49.520
And he didn't do it quite in time, we don't
know if he actually did but didn't wanna tell

00:45:49.520 --> 00:45:56.030
them, but he'd almost completed it by the
time he was liberated by the Russians.

00:45:56.030 --> 00:46:00.520
Then in the years after the war worked out
how to do it, tried to get funding, the only

00:46:00.520 --> 00:46:04.760
people who he could get funding was the Duchy
of Liechtenstein. So he moved to Liechtenstein

00:46:04.760 --> 00:46:12.560
and for basically up until the late '60s this
